Europe
------
[1] Russia (Khanty-Mansi)
Date: Sun 17 Aug 2014
Source: NewsProm.Ru [in Russian, transl., summ., edited]
http://newsprom.ru/news/Proisshestvija/201593.html


10 cases of measles have been recorded in the Nizhnevartovsk Region [Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug]. All diagnoses have been supported by laboratory tests. None of the patients had been vaccinated. According to local physicians, unfortunately some members of the population were resistant to measures designed to improve their own health and those of other members of the population. In addition, every parent should know that attendance of their children at school is not permitted during the entire quarantine period. The source of the disease may be another sick person during the period of incubation of the disease (about 3-4 days before the rash appears), and during the 1st 5 days after the onset of rash. The incubation period lasts about 10 days, but can vary up to 17 days.

Symptoms of measles virus infection are:
- Body temperature rises to 38-39 deg C [100.4-102 deg F]. This is accompanied by a runny nose, dry cough, lacrimation and photophobia. This period is called catarrhal; it has a duration of 3 to 5.6 days. By its end temperature is slightly lowered and kept within 37.5-38 deg C [about 99.5-100.4 deg F].
- A day or 2 before the rash, small whitish spots on the buccal mucosa may appear; sometimes arranged in clusters around small molars. These spots are present for 2-3 days, and are a common symptom [sign] of measles.
- This is followed by the appearance of a rash when the temperature rises back to 40 deg C [104 deg F], before falling again after 5-7 days.
- In some cases, complications (such as laryngitis) may develop subsequently, often accompanied by inflammation of the lungs or purulent inflammation of the middle ear.

In Russia, measles vaccination is conducted in accordance with the National Immunization Schedule in 18 months. Adults aged 18-35 years are not vaccinated. Those without a history of prior measles virus infection, and with no prior documentary evidence of vaccination, are inoculated twice with an interval of at least 3 months between treatments.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Nizhnevartovsk is the 2nd largest city in Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug (KMAO), Russia, located along the right bank of the River Ob. Maps can be accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nizhnevartovsk and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2716808,462. Previously measles has been reported in other parts of the KMAO and its neighbour Tyumen. - Mod.CP]

******
[2] Russia (Khanty-Mansi)
Date: Wed 20 Aug 2014
Source: AIF.ru, Arguments and Facts [in Russian, transl., summ., edited]
http://www.ugra.aif.ru/health/1320603


13 suspected cases of measles have been hospitalised in Nizhnevartovsk (Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug). One of the cases is a less-than-one-year-old child who had not been vaccinated, but whose mother had gone through the full course of vaccination. 3 cases comprise children younger than 7 years, and one child is less than a year, according to the Federal Service of Ugra.

Of the 13 cases, 12 were hospitalized in infectious disease departments, and the remaining one is receiving treatment on an outpatient basis, according to the press agency.

