[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Fri 22 Aug 2014
Source: Whitsunday Times [edited]
http://www.whitsundaytimes.com.au/news/measles-outbreak-whitsundays/2361055/


Whitsunday [Queensland] residents are urged to contact their local health services in regards to a measles outbreak that was announced today [22 Aug 2014] from Mackay Hospital and Health Service. It has been reported that an adult male visiting from overseas has had contact with extended family, friends and in the community while infected. Mackay Hospital and Health Service Public Health Physician Doctor Stephen Donohue said a large number of people at a Whitsundays resort for a wedding have been exposed.

A measles alert has been issued for people who were visiting Montes Reef Resort at Hydeaway Bay on Friday, 15 Aug 2014, Cape Gloucester Beach Resort Hydeaway Bay on Friday, 15 Aug 2014 and Saturday, 16 Aug 2014 and La Tabella Trattoria on Airlie Beach Esplanade on Sunday, 17 Aug 2014. Anyone who also visited the following Mackay locations this week should also be warned: One Stop Centre on Tuesday, 19 Aug 2014 and MIMS Clinic Mackay Mater Hospital on Wednesday, 20 Aug 2014.

GPs and hospitals have been notified of the possibility of measles cases presenting. Measles is a highly infectious and serious viral infection that causes fever, cough, runny nose, sore eyes, and then a red spotty rash a few days later. It is often a severe disease and occasionally measles has dangerous complications.

Queensland Health recommends anyone born during or since 1966, who has not had 2 documented doses of measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine or had proven measles, should visit their local GP to get vaccinated for measles.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Whitsunday group of islands lie off the northeast Queensland coast. These islands attract a large number of tourists throughout the year, and outbreaks of measles virus infection are frequent and not a seasonal phenomenon similar to the seasonal occurrence in the northern and southern hemispheres. Visitors to these resorts should ensure that their vaccination record is appropriate. - Mod.CP]

******
[6] Solomon Islands
Date: Fri 22 Aug 2014
Source: Solomon Times Online, MHMS press release [summ., edited]
http://www.solomontimes.com/news/200-measles-cases-reported/8268


Cases of measles in the Solomon Islands continue to rise with over 200 reported, the majority of which are in Honiara [Honiara Province]. Parents need to act quickly and vaccinate their children aged 6 months to 4 years and 11 months against this potentially deadly disease, warns the Ministry of Health and Medical Services (MHMS), World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF. "Parents need to protect their children from measles. The best way of doing this is by taking them to a local health clinic for a measles vaccination. The vaccine is safe, effective and free. It will prevent their children from 'catching' the disease," said Dr. Lester Ross, Permanent Secretary of MHMS. "Even if a child has had one dose of the measles vaccine, parents of 1 year to 4 years and 11-month-old children should take them back to their health clinic for a 2nd dose, immediately," added Dr. Ross. "It is also important that parents remember to take their child's baby book so that they can keep a record of their child's vaccinations," concluded Dr. Ross. There is no treatment for measles, only medication to relieve the symptoms. MHMS, WHO and UNICEF are working together to control the measles outbreak in Solomon Islands.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Solomon Islands is sovereign country consisting of a large number of islands in Oceania lying to the east of Papua New Guinea and northwest of Vanuatu and covering a land area of 28 400 sq km [about 11 000 sq miles]. The country's capital, Honiara, is located on the island of Guadalcanal. Solomon Islands should not be confused with the Solomon Islands archipelago, which is a collection of Melanesian islands that includes Solomon Islands and Bougainville Island. The population of Solomon Islands was approximately 523 000 in 2009, so the current measles outbreak is a serious event. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2716808,189.]
